According to review aggregator [[Metacritic]], ''Murdering Oscar (And Other Love Songs)'' has a score of 80/100, indicating "generally favorable reviews".<ref name=MC>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/murdering-oscar-and-other-love-songs/patterson-hood|title=Reviews for Murdering Oscar (And Other Love Songs) by Patterson Hood - Metacritic|accessdate=November 13, 2017|publisher=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref> Several critics described ''Murdering Oscar''{{'}}s music as more intimate and personal than Hood's previous work with the Drive-By Truckers.<ref name=tucker/><ref name=nytimes>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/22/arts/music/22choice.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | title=New CDs | work=[[New York Times]] | date=June 21, 2009 | accessdate=October 7, 2014 | author=Pareles, Jon | authorlink=Jon Pareles}}</ref> [[Jon Pareles]] also noted that Hood's music on ''Murdering Oscar'' discusses both depressing topics, such as murder and suicide, as well as more positive ones such as "family and continuity" on "I Understand Now".<ref name=nytimes/> Joshua Klein wrote that Hood was "surprisingly sanguine, even mature" in the way he addressed both positive and negative topics on the album,<ref name=pitchfork/> and [[AllMusic]]'s [[Mark Deming]] said that its songs were "dark but compassionate character studies," adding that it "consistently cuts closer to the bone" than Hood's debut solo album ''Killers and Stars'' (2004).<ref name=allmusic/> [[Greg Kot]] gave ''Murdering Oscar'' three stars out of four and wrote that it "maintains a certain raw immediacy."<ref name=trib>{{cite web | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-06-23/entertainment/0906230075_1_love-songs-drive-by-truckers-patterson-hood | title=Patterson Hood, "Murdering Oscar (and Other Love Songs)" | work=[[Chicago Tribune]] | date=June 23, 2009 | accessdate=October 16, 2014 | author=Kot, Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot}}</ref>

Different critics made different comparisons between the album and the work Hood did with the Drive-By Truckers: [[Ken Tucker]] wrote that "Where the music made by the Drive-By Truckers can expand to epic proportions without becoming overblown, Hood's solo songs are smaller scale, more intimate",<ref name=tucker>{{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=106093822 | title=Patterson Hood: Drive-By Boss Does 'Murder' | website=[[NPR]] | date=June 30, 2009 | accessdate=May 15, 2014 | author=Tucker, Ken}}</ref> while ''PopMatters''{{'}} Stuart Henderson wrote that "None of the songs here would be out of place on either of the last two Truckers albums", and that "[t]he sound, then, remains the same, but just a little less the same."<ref name=popmatters/> Henderson also argued that the music of ''Murdering Oscar'' discusses variations on the story of "the lonely, forgotten everyman", which he called one of Hood's favorite themes.<ref name=popmatters/> Jesse Cataldo, writing in ''Slant'', criticized the album for being far inferior to Hood's work with the Truckers, saying that on ''Murdering Oscar'', "Hood falters, resulting in an uninterrupted stream of watery drivel that drifts by much too slowly."<ref name="slant">{{cite web | url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/patterson-hood-murdering-oscar-and-other-love-songs | title=Murdering Oscar (And Other Love Songs) | work=[[Slant Magazine]]| date=June 15, 2009 | accessdate=October 16, 2014 | author=Cataldo, Jesse}}</ref> He attributed this in part to the absence of the Truckers' other songwriter, [[Mike Cooley (musician)|Mike Cooley]].<ref name=slant/> It was ranked 316th on ''[[the Village Voice]]''{{'}}s 2009 [[Pazz & Jop]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/albums/2009/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100219231042/http://www.villagevoice.com/pazznjop/albums/2009/|archivedate=February 19, 2010 | title=Albums — All Votes | publisher=[[Village Voice]] | accessdate=7 October 2014}}</ref> 39th on [[Robert Christgau]]'s 2009 "Dean's List",<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/deans09.php | title=2009: Dean's List | publisher=Robert Christgau | accessdate=October 7, 2014 | author=Christgau, Robert}}</ref> and was named the fifth best album of 2009 by [[Steven Hyden]] of ''[[the A.V. Club]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://music.avclub.com/the-best-music-of-2009-the-ballots-1798219933| title=The best music of 2009: The Ballots | website=[[The A.V. Club]] | date=December 2009 | accessdate=5 May 2017 | author=The A.V. Club Staff}}</ref> It peaked at number 153 on the ''[[Billboard 200]]'' on July 11, 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/music/patterson-hood| title=Patterson Hood - Chart History | work=Billboard | accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T0sB47TxoCwC&pg=PT38 | title=The Billboard 200 | journal=Billboard | date=11 July 2009|page=39|volume=121|issue=27 | accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref>

